com.ibm.team.scm.common

Interface IChangeSet

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IAuditable, IAuditableHandle, IChangeSetHandle, IItem, IItemHandle, IManagedItem, IManagedItemHandle

    public interface IChangeSet
extends IChangeSetHandle, IAuditable
    Represents a change set. A change set describes one or more changes to versionable items in a configuration. Applying those changes yield another configuration. In other words, a change set is a reified configuration delta.

    A change set has a unique id (UUID) and changes (check-ins, comment changes, etc.) create new change set states. There is a current state and all other states provide an audit trail (see IAuditable for more details).

    Since configurations are typically large, and change sets typically, the standard usage is to explicitly construct a change set that can be applied to a configuration. Computing a change set by diffing two configurations to not done for reasons of performance (although it would make sense in principle to do so).

    Note that there are no operations on IChangeSet that modify the change set directly. A change set gets constructed and modified indirectly in the course of changing files, folders, and other versionable items in a workspace. When an aspect of the change set is modified, a new state of the change set is created. Clients are not permitted to save change sets. They are, however, allowed to retrieve a change set with fetchCurrent, fetchState, etc.

    Since:
    0.5

      • getLastChangeDate

        java.util.Date getLastChangeDate()
        Returns the time in which this change set was last changed in the context of a workspace. This timestamp changes when the change set is created, closed or when the nested changes are altered in any way. Updating the comment does not update this timestamp.
        Returns:
        the time at which the change set was updated; never null

      • getOriginalSourceId

        UUID getOriginalSourceId()
        Returns the logical id that can be used to group this change set with other change sets porting the same logical change set. It indicates this change set is a port (possibly through porting other ports of a change set) or itself has been ported (it may be the original change set).
        Returns:
        The id of the port that this change set represents. May be null if this change set is not a port of another change set (or has never been ported).

      • getSourceChangeSet

        IChangeSetHandle getSourceChangeSet()
        Returns:
        The change set that was ported resulting in this change set. Maybe null if this change set does not represent a port or if the source of the port was something other than a change set.

      • getOriginalChangeSet

        IChangeSetHandle getOriginalChangeSet()
        The original change set ported resulting in the group of change sets with the same port id. If this change set is the original change set that has been ported in other change sets, the result would be the item handle for this change set. If this change set is the result of a direct port of another change set, then the result is the same as getSourceChangeSet(). If this is a port of a port of a ... this is the change set that was originally ported at the very beginning.
        Returns:
        The change set that was originally ported. May be null if this change set or has never been ported or if the source of the port was something other than a change set.
